thing we're going to release

00:11:59.810 --> 00:12:02.490
and then skipping right to--
it's like step one underpants,

00:12:02.490 --> 00:12:03.350
step three profit.

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:05.840
It's like, we all talk
about these communities

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:07.560
and building these
huge ecosystems

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:09.800
but a lot of
projects, they never

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:13.080
get to that first
external contributor.

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:15.840
So what would you do to
help a project get there

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:18.230
or what have you done to
help a project get there?

00:12:18.230 --> 00:12:22.240
Maybe it's in a sub
library of Go, or--

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:24.560
Yeah, I'm very curious.

00:12:24.560 --> 00:12:27.200
Because I honestly, I
have the hardest time

00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:29.000
with this question.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.949
SARAH NOVOTNY: So I'll
jump in because in my team,

00:12:31.949 --> 00:12:33.740
we have a number of
people that are working

00:12:33.740 --> 00:12:35.750
across a number of
projects and some of them

00:12:35.750 --> 00:12:39.200
are at very early stages.

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:42.650
There are projects that
have been recently released.

00:12:42.650 --> 00:12:46.620
There are projects that have
been out for eight years.

00:12:46.620 --> 00:12:50.240
And so there's this whole
gamut within the lifecycle.

00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:55.490
The new projects,
one of the best ways

00:12:55.490 --> 00:12:59.840
to get new people involved
and get people excited

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:03.500
is to be an advocate
in that project.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:08.870
And so that means that it is
easier and more successful

00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:12.500
if someone who is already
participating in a project

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:14.660
is super excited
about it and starts

00:13:14.660 --> 00:13:17.690
drawing in their friends,
starts drawing in the people

00:13:17.690 --> 00:13:21.260
that they know, starts
talking about it on Twitter,

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:24.590
starts just sharing
that excitement.

00:13:24.590 --> 00:13:28.970
And those projects start
to take off and start

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:34.460
to build just a reinforcement
of that advocacy,

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:36.590
if you can share
your excitement.

00:13:36.590 --> 00:13:38.836
If you're doing this
because it's horrible,

00:13:38.836 --> 00:13:40.460
and it just needs to
be fixed, and then

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:42.320
I'm going to open
source it, it's

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:45.830
not likely to take off
as a broader project.

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:49.100
But if you can say why this
is super neat and why you are

00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:53.390
so excited about fixing it,
or making this available

00:13:53.390 --> 00:13:57.950
to the broader community, or
how it fits in another community

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:03.779
and bootstrap off of that, then
you find like-minded people--

00:14:03.779 --> 00:14:04.820
they may be your friends.

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:06.300
There may be other
people trying to solve

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:07.460
the same sort of problem.

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:10.850
And you can invigorate
their interest.

00:14:10.850 --> 00:14:12.800
But it does take
some evangelism.

00:14:16.087 --> 00:14:18.170
WILL NORRIS: I would say
one of the key things you

00:14:18.170 --> 00:14:21.050
can do is to make sure
that your project is ready

00:14:21.050 --> 00:14:23.840
and welcoming to newcomers.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:27.500
And so, this comes down
a lot of times to the way

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:31.070
that you manage your community
and just the documentation.

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:33.980
We find that from projects
that had participated

00:14:33.980 --> 00:14:36.740
in the Summer of Code
in previous years,

00:14:36.740 --> 00:14:40.220
even if the work that the
students did on that project--

00:14:40.220 --> 00:14:42.200
I mean, maybe it was
great, maybe it wasn't.

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:45.500
But invariably,
those projects end up

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:49.840
having to focus so much on their
getting started documentation,

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:52.310
of making sure that they
have a clear guide for people

00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:54.900
to get up and running in a
very short amount of time.

00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:58.310
And those kinds of changes
really stick with the project

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:01.530
and just make the project
welcoming in general.

00:15:01.530 --> 00:15:03.500
One of the things we
encourage a lot-- and this

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:04.640
is pretty common.

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:08.030
--is having a set of
issues on your project

00:15:08.030 --> 00:15:10.870
that are specifically
labeled for beginners,

00:15:10.870 --> 00:15:14.480
like beginner tasks that the
core team doesn't work on.

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:16.130
And they intentionally
don't work on it

00:15:16.130 --> 00:15:22.640
so that when that newcomer
comes there's a really bite size

00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:24.440
issue that they can fix.

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:27.850
And that really eases--
setting them up for success,

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:30.835
I think is really kind
of where I would say.

00:15:30.835 --> 00:15:32.210
SARAH NOVOTNY: To
that point, you

00:15:32.210 --> 00:15:36.140
can use those new contributors
to help with that onboarding

00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:38.314
process, cause they get stuck.

00:15:38.314 --> 00:15:39.230
You say, that's great.

00:15:39.230 --> 00:15:40.610
Lets document this.

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:43.890
And then you work with them
to improve that process.

00:15:43.890 --> 00:15:47.540
WILL NORRIS: One of the most
valuable perspectives I think,

00:15:47.540 --> 00:15:49.940
is the person who doesn't know.

00:15:49.940 --> 00:15:52.820
And it's so valuable because
you lose that perspective

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:54.420
so quickly.

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:56.150
And we find this
internally at Google

00:15:56.150 --> 00:15:58.490
because Google is structured
so that you can move around

00:15:58.490 --> 00:16:00.240
between teams very easily.

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:02.000
And so there's a
lot of mobility.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.240
And when that new person
comes to your team,

00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:07.460
you have to take
advantage of that time.

00:16:07.460 --> 00:16:10.080
It's like you've got a very
short window before they start

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:12.530
learning all that
institutional knowledge that

00:16:12.530 --> 00:16:14.550
never gets written down.

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:16.160
And so you've got
to write it down

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:19.730
when that person
is first coming on.

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:22.790
CASSANDRA SALISBURY: Kind
of piggybacking off of that.

00:16:22.790 --> 00:16:27.350
I totally want to just point
out the cross-promotion of,

00:16:27.350 --> 00:16:28.710
with other communities.

00:16:28.710 --> 00:16:29.210
Right?

00:16:29.210 --> 00:16:34.270
Because we've seen that on
a massive scale with Go,

00:16:34.270 --> 00:16:36.810
in Kubernetes, in Docker.

00:16:36.810 --> 00:16:40.610
I used to run a meet up
in San Francisco for Go.

00:16:40.610 --> 00:16:43.910
And the amount of
evangelists, kind

00:16:43.910 --> 00:16:49.010
of naturally coming to that
and doing speaking engagements,

00:16:49.010 --> 00:16:51.920
really perpetuates that
level of like, ooh, this

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:53.580
sounds really awesome.

00:16:53.580 --> 00:16:56.630
So five years ago,
I'm looking at, oh, I

00:16:56.630 --> 00:17:00.830
heard that one meet up, that one
time, that one talk, and it's

00:17:00.830 --> 00:17:04.020
exploded just because people
are willing to talk about it.

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:07.339
I also think-- of
off Will's point--

00:17:07.339 --> 00:17:10.430
in a smaller project that I
worked on prior to Google,

00:17:10.430 --> 00:17:15.839
labeling in GitHub was a huge
help for new contributors.

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:18.800
And then after-- since we've
talked about the getting

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:23.329
of the contributors-- after you
have a nice little, small pool,

00:17:23.329 --> 00:17:26.000
we would do weekly
meetings with them

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.831
for like 30 minutes
just to encourage them

00:17:28.831 --> 00:17:30.830
and to make them feel
like they were really part

00:17:30.830 --> 00:17:33.480
of a collaborative process.

00:17:33.480 --> 00:17:35.660
SARAH NOVOTNY: Which
ends up leading to making

00:17:35.660 --> 00:17:37.790
the feeling of a tribe.

00:17:37.790 --> 00:17:41.900
So you need to have some sort
of cohesive group feeling

00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:44.905
in order to join
and participate.

00:17:44.905 --> 00:17:46.280
And you have to
feel as if you're

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:51.560
making some sort of contribution
that is recognized and valued.

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:57.290
And every community needs to
have that space where you are

00:17:57.290 --> 00:18:00.210
able to say, I participated.

00:18:00.210 --> 00:18:06.260
I met the luminary who
wrote Go, the luminary who

00:18:06.260 --> 00:18:07.940
started Kubernetes.

00:18:07.940 --> 00:18:13.100
And then there's this
sense of togetherness.

00:18:13.100 --> 00:18:17.120
You end up aligning a group of
people in a single direction.

00:18:17.120 --> 00:18:20.360
And you can't understate
how valuable--

00:18:20.360 --> 00:18:24.290
or you can't overstate
how valuable that is.

00:18:24.290 --> 00:18:28.354
CHRIS DIBONA: So before I ask my
