And in about 10 minutes, if
you want to ask, we'll see.

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:36.110
There's there and there.

00:18:36.110 --> 00:18:40.070
So we say this word
community a lot.

00:18:40.070 --> 00:18:44.870
It's kind of, in some ways,
the least defined thing ever.

00:18:44.870 --> 00:18:46.930
And we say, open, a lot.

00:18:46.930 --> 00:18:50.800
And I'm not going to say
it's frustrating for me

00:18:50.800 --> 00:18:56.360
but I've always tried
to be really annoyingly

00:18:56.360 --> 00:18:58.940
particular about this.

00:18:58.940 --> 00:19:03.110
And so when you say
community, when you say,

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:06.470
open, and I think,
open source software

00:19:06.470 --> 00:19:08.090
licensed under an
open sourced license

00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:12.050
and offered to the public.

00:19:12.050 --> 00:19:13.830
But what does it mean to you?

00:19:13.830 --> 00:19:20.690
What is your gold standard of
how you like to best interact

00:19:20.690 --> 00:19:24.440
technically in these projects?

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:26.140
So I just--

00:19:26.140 --> 00:19:30.020
And I know this is partly
me projecting but--

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:34.800
CASSANDRA SALISBURY:
If I'm looking at,

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:39.660
what does it take
to be open, then I'm

00:19:39.660 --> 00:19:42.840
looking at transparency.

00:19:42.840 --> 00:19:47.340
Do we know why decisions
are being made in a project?

00:19:47.340 --> 00:19:50.110
Can we see clear paths?

00:19:50.110 --> 00:19:54.000
Is documentation
transparent, easy to follow?

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.070
I'm looking at collaboration.

00:19:57.070 --> 00:20:00.990
So, how easy is it to
contribute to the process?

00:20:00.990 --> 00:20:02.490
Does it feel collaborative?

00:20:02.490 --> 00:20:04.140
Are people interacting?

00:20:04.140 --> 00:20:05.820
Are they meeting at conferences?

00:20:05.820 --> 00:20:09.090
Are they interacting on
a slack or a channel?

00:20:09.090 --> 00:20:13.920
And then I think, lastly,
it would be inclusivity,

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:16.650
making sure that
there's an openness

00:20:16.650 --> 00:20:20.130
of all types of
opinions and needs,

00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:21.930
and that they're
being listened to.

00:20:21.930 --> 00:20:24.090
And that people
feel it's easy to,

00:20:24.090 --> 00:20:28.950
again, just have access and
feel included in the process.

00:20:28.950 --> 00:20:31.590
SARAH NOVOTNY: I think there's
another underpinning component

00:20:31.590 --> 00:20:35.400
to all of those, which
is respect for all

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:37.600
the people participating.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:43.560
And it goes back to Will's point
that that newcomer's view--

00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:47.280
even if you don't see it and
it seems perfectly obvious how

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:49.620
you should get from A to C--

00:20:49.620 --> 00:20:55.320
that newcomer's view is gold
because there is friction

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:55.950
there.

00:20:55.950 --> 00:20:57.900
And that friction,
if it's not going

00:20:57.900 --> 00:21:00.300
to be a contributor
who drops out,

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:02.310
it might be user who drops out.

00:21:02.310 --> 00:21:05.110
And so you're decreasing
your adoption.

00:21:05.110 --> 00:21:09.630
So you have this adoption curve,
or this contributor curve,

00:21:09.630 --> 00:21:12.150
where it's like, everybody who
thinks the Kubernetes might

00:21:12.150 --> 00:21:13.630
be awesome.

00:21:13.630 --> 00:21:16.740
And then everybody who
has read CONTRIBUTING.md

00:21:16.740 --> 00:21:18.990
and maybe got stymied by it.

00:21:18.990 --> 00:21:20.760
And then suddenly
you've got a list

00:21:20.760 --> 00:21:23.400
of people who did understand
what we were saying

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:25.350
because we actually
forgot to mention

00:21:25.350 --> 00:21:29.340
that K8S means Kubernetes.

00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:31.710
And then you've got
this group who's

00:21:31.710 --> 00:21:35.700
bothered to stick around
long enough to actually go

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:36.990
through all these hurdles.

00:21:36.990 --> 00:21:40.380
And so you've decreased
the number of people,

00:21:40.380 --> 00:21:43.320
and the people that
you're engaging with,

00:21:43.320 --> 00:21:46.830
a lot, if you're not respecting
that newcomer view, if you're

00:21:46.830 --> 00:21:51.180
not respecting the challenges
and feedback that people

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:52.590
are bringing to you.

00:21:52.590 --> 00:21:55.020
So that, to me, is one of
the core pieces of openness.

00:21:57.920 --> 00:21:59.120
CHRIS DIBONA: Will--

00:21:59.120 --> 00:22:00.290
SARAH NOVOTNY: Licenses.

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:02.060
Sorry.

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:03.800
WILL NORRIS: No, I would say--

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:06.960
maybe provide a slightly
different perspective,

00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:10.250
which is, we've
often said at Google

00:22:10.250 --> 00:22:13.340
that there's no one
way to do open source.

00:22:13.340 --> 00:22:15.080
And I really do believe that.

00:22:15.080 --> 00:22:17.450
And that's true in so
many different ways,

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:21.110
in terms of licenses, in
terms of governance models,

00:22:21.110 --> 00:22:24.500
in terms of community
management styles.

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:27.009
And Google is big enough that--

00:22:27.009 --> 00:22:28.550
Sarah was making
this point earlier--

00:22:28.550 --> 00:22:31.250
that even within the eight or so
projects that they engage with,

00:22:31.250 --> 00:22:32.630
there's a lot of variety.

00:22:32.630 --> 00:22:35.570
Within the thousands of
projects that Google releases,

00:22:35.570 --> 00:22:37.640
there is a huge
amount of variety.

00:22:37.640 --> 00:22:40.370
And it really comes
back to, why did you

00:22:40.370 --> 00:22:41.959
open-source it to begin with?

00:22:41.959 --> 00:22:44.000
And it's going to be
different for every project.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.766
And so that gold standard
really depends on,

00:22:47.766 --> 00:22:49.640
what were the goals of
releasing that project

00:22:49.640 --> 00:22:51.260
in the first place?

00:22:51.260 --> 00:22:53.709
And that's going to guide how
you make a lot of decisions.

00:22:53.709 --> 00:22:56.000
And that's something that
Sarah and I have been working

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.910
on together for a little
while is, helping provide

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:02.900
that guidance for teams at
Google to really think through,

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:05.000
why are they releasing
it as open source,

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:09.110
and then, let that
dictate how they answer

00:23:09.110 --> 00:23:10.650
a lot of these other questions.

00:23:10.650 --> 00:23:15.740
SARAH NOVOTNY: You also have
the spectrum between open source

00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:20.120
software, to an
open source project,

00:23:20.120 --> 00:23:24.860
to an open inclusive community,
which is even further.

00:23:24.860 --> 00:23:28.070
So open source
software, I often define

00:23:28.070 --> 00:23:31.520
as code that is
publicly available

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:37.400
and has a license that
the OSI has checkboxed,

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:40.140
said, this is an
open source license.

00:23:40.140 --> 00:23:42.020
So that would be
open source software.

00:23:42.020 --> 00:23:44.060
Doesn't mean you get
an opinion on it.

00:23:44.060 --> 00:23:46.910
It doesn't mean you get
to contribute or change it

00:23:46.910 --> 00:23:47.690
but it's open.

00:23:47.690 --> 00:23:48.440
It's available.

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:50.360
It is-- you're free to use it.

00:23:50.360 --> 00:23:52.190
You're free to look at it.

00:23:52.190 --> 00:23:53.180
You're free to fork it.

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:55.050
You're free to change
it on your own.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:58.400
But you may not be able to
modify the core software

00:23:58.400 --> 00:23:59.910
as it stands.

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:03.800
But as you move toward, down the
progression and the continuum

00:24:03.800 --> 00:24:06.470
toward project, it
becomes much more

00:24:06.470 --> 00:24:09.740
about pulling together a
cohesive community that

00:24:09.740 --> 00:24:14.210
is looking to solve a
larger problem than any one

00:24:14.210 --> 00:24:17.330
perspective can
accurately scope.

00:24:17.330 --> 00:24:21.740
Sort of the blind men trying
to describe an elephant.

00:24:21.740 --> 00:24:24.290
Each different piece
of your community

00:24:24.290 --> 00:24:27.590
comes to the project bringing
you a different perspective.

00:24:27.590 --> 00:24:30.410
And this is one of the
things we saw in Kubernetes.

00:24:30.410 --> 00:24:35.030
Google had a very opinionated
way of dealing with containers.

00:24:35.030 --> 00:24:35.930
We built Bork.

00:24:35.930 --> 00:24:37.160
We built Omega.

00:24:37.160 --> 00:24:39.620
We knew Kubernetes
was going to be

00:24:39.620 --> 00:24:42.230
a thing that the
world needed but we

00:24:42.230 --> 00:24:44.330
needed more perspectives.

00:24:44.330 --> 00:24:47.240
And so that had to
be an open community.

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:49.280
That is not every project.

00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:53.340
And that is not every project
that is released by anyone.

00:24:53.340 --> 00:24:55.550
It's not every project
released by Google.

00:24:55.550 --> 00:24:58.940
Android, as an example,
has fewer people

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:00.740
contributing and
changing the way

00:25:00.740 --> 00:25:05.660
the Android open source
project moves from outside

00:25:05.660 --> 00:25:08.060
of Google than many--

00:25:08.060 --> 00:25:09.590
than Kubernetes at this--

00:25:09.590 --> 00:25:13.970
well, maybe not direct
numbers because of the years,

00:25:13.970 --> 00:25:17.240
but there are different
amounts of influence

00:25:17.240 --> 00:25:22.660
based on the strategic
goals of the project.

