00:25:27.690 --> 00:25:32.880
but what's wrong with how
we release code from Google?

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:35.340
What would you want
to see different?

00:25:35.340 --> 00:25:36.870
What's hard?

00:25:36.870 --> 00:25:39.540
What problems have you
seen when releasing code

00:25:39.540 --> 00:25:40.610
from the company?

00:25:40.610 --> 00:25:43.151
Because I have people from other
big companies come to me all

00:25:43.151 --> 00:25:45.380
the time and say, wow, you
released a lot of stuff

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:47.963
but you didn't release this one
thing I wanted you to release.

00:25:47.963 --> 00:25:49.390
And I'm like, eh, you know.

00:25:49.390 --> 00:25:52.890
So tell me how we could
be doing a better job

00:25:52.890 --> 00:25:55.475
and how we could all
be doing a better job.

00:25:55.475 --> 00:25:57.850
WILL NORRIS: I'd know the
answer to that one immediately.

00:25:57.850 --> 00:26:00.224
And it really relates to what
we were just talking about,

00:26:00.224 --> 00:26:02.910
that there is no one
way to do open-source.

00:26:02.910 --> 00:26:06.880
We could absolutely do a better
job of setting expectations,

00:26:06.880 --> 00:26:09.810
that when you find a random
project in one of our GitHub

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:15.130
orgs, or on googlesource.com,
or wherever you find a project,

00:26:15.130 --> 00:26:19.600
is this a project that is being
used in production at Google?

00:26:19.600 --> 00:26:21.180
Is this being
actively developed?

00:26:21.180 --> 00:26:25.080
Is it looking for community?

00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:29.010
Or is this just a project that
is intended to be consumed

00:26:29.010 --> 00:26:31.840
but maybe not collaborated on?

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:35.520
And we can-- you can argue
on which one is better

00:26:35.520 --> 00:26:39.840
and all of that but regardless
of any of that, just

00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:42.270
setting the right
expectation is something

00:26:42.270 --> 00:26:45.630
that we could absolutely
do a better job of.

00:26:45.630 --> 00:26:48.420
CASSANDRA SALISBURY:
For the Go project,

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:51.090
we do have a really
collaborative-- we

00:26:51.090 --> 00:26:53.100
want contributors, et cetera.

00:26:53.100 --> 00:26:56.430
And so, some of the
things that we've learned

00:26:56.430 --> 00:27:01.830
would be, ask for opinions
and contributions early on.

00:27:01.830 --> 00:27:04.890
So if you are going
to release then--

00:27:04.890 --> 00:27:07.970
sometimes we get feedback
from behind the doors,

00:27:07.970 --> 00:27:10.830
so that when you do you get
a little bit less of a nudge

00:27:10.830 --> 00:27:12.240
there.

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:18.506
But I think even more so,
it is that you need to--

00:27:18.506 --> 00:27:20.130
exactly what you're
saying, Will-- it's

00:27:20.130 --> 00:27:23.040
an iterative process,
usually, when you

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:25.080
have a collaborative project.

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:26.340
It's all iterative.

00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:28.830
And so that's the one thing
we've learned is, be clear.

00:27:28.830 --> 00:27:32.790
Yes, it may not be perfect
when it is first released

00:27:32.790 --> 00:27:34.405
but it's all iterative.

00:27:34.405 --> 00:27:36.030
And the reason we do
that is because we

00:27:36.030 --> 00:27:37.554
want those contributions.

00:27:37.554 --> 00:27:38.970
WILL NORRIS: And
just being honest

00:27:38.970 --> 00:27:41.817
and transparent about where a
project is along that spectrum.

00:27:41.817 --> 00:27:42.900
CASSANDRA SALISBURY: Yeah.

00:27:42.900 --> 00:27:44.816
SARAH NOVOTNY: I'm willing
to go out on a limb

00:27:44.816 --> 00:27:48.070
and say, I guarantee it won't be
perfect when it goes out first.

00:27:48.070 --> 00:27:48.640
CASSANDRA SALISBURY:
No, it for sure won't.

00:27:48.640 --> 00:27:49.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:49.340 --> 00:27:49.840
Yeah.

00:27:49.840 --> 00:27:51.120
No, for sure.

00:27:51.120 --> 00:27:54.900
SARAH NOVOTNY: But to
Will's point, making sure

00:27:54.900 --> 00:28:00.060
that we are setting expectations
is important but also showing

00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:03.000
growth paths, showing how
someone can contribute,

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:07.290
and how they can continue
to engage with the project,

00:28:07.290 --> 00:28:10.680
showing where the
project needs are,

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:17.040
and making sure that when we
are engaging with the community,

00:28:17.040 --> 00:28:19.470
that their feedback
is recognized,

00:28:19.470 --> 00:28:20.750
even if it isn't followed.

00:28:25.519 --> 00:28:27.810
CHRIS DIBONA: So should I
ask about contributor license

00:28:27.810 --> 00:28:29.016
agreements and DCOs?

00:28:29.016 --> 00:28:29.516
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:29.516 --> 00:28:31.920
I mean, how much
actual problems do you

00:28:31.920 --> 00:28:36.930
see around the apparatus
of intellectual property

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:39.461
actually keeping you from
getting contributors and all

00:28:39.461 --> 00:28:39.960
the rest.

00:28:39.960 --> 00:28:42.126
Because this is something
we talk about quite a bit.

00:28:42.126 --> 00:28:43.280
We are a big company.

00:28:43.280 --> 00:28:46.350
So we care a lot about
where software comes from,

00:28:46.350 --> 00:28:50.820
who's writing it, who owns that
intellectual property as it's

00:28:50.820 --> 00:28:53.610
released, and we have to be
very, very careful about it

00:28:53.610 --> 00:28:55.520
because we get sued a lot.

00:28:55.520 --> 00:28:58.890
So I'd be really
interested in hearing

00:28:58.890 --> 00:29:03.300
if you've seen a real
problem because of that or--

00:29:03.300 --> 00:29:04.680
because--

00:29:04.680 --> 00:29:06.780
WILL NORRIS: You
see it occasionally.

00:29:06.780 --> 00:29:09.510
For the most part, the
biggest problems we see

00:29:09.510 --> 00:29:12.540
are just weird edge cases
that our automated tooling

00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:13.710
can't handle.

00:29:13.710 --> 00:29:16.380
And so a fair amount of my
time, and my team's time,

00:29:16.380 --> 00:29:18.496
is spent dealing with
those edge cases,

00:29:18.496 --> 00:29:20.120
and walking people
through the process,

00:29:20.120 --> 00:29:21.810
and figuring it all out.

00:29:21.810 --> 00:29:24.030
We will occasionally
see someone who

00:29:24.030 --> 00:29:27.240
just is adamant about not
wanting to sign a contributor

00:29:27.240 --> 00:29:28.950
license agreement.

00:29:28.950 --> 00:29:31.638
And in those cases,
we have to say,

00:29:31.638 --> 00:29:33.762
I'm sorry this is just
something that we do require

00:29:33.762 --> 00:29:36.380
for a variety of reasons.

00:29:36.380 --> 00:29:38.820
And we've seen time
and time again,

00:29:38.820 --> 00:29:43.530
where having that contributor
license agreement has saved us,

00:29:43.530 --> 00:29:47.140
or has allowed us a
degree of flexibility.

00:29:47.140 --> 00:29:50.490
For example, we relicensed
Angular a few years ago.

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:53.680
We originally released it
under the Apache 2 license.

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:56.010
The community-- the
JavaScript community

00:29:56.010 --> 00:29:58.140
largely preferred MIT.

00:29:58.140 --> 00:30:00.630
And so we talked about it
and we made that decision

00:30:00.630 --> 00:30:03.810
to relicense the project
under MIT, at the community's

00:30:03.810 --> 00:30:04.830
request.

00:30:04.830 --> 00:30:07.250
This was something that was
only possible because we

00:30:07.250 --> 00:30:09.000
had contributor license
agreements for all

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:12.170
of those contributors.

00:30:12.170 --> 00:30:14.070
SARAH NOVOTNY: And I'll
play devil's advocate

00:30:14.070 --> 00:30:17.100
because Kubernetes was
a challenge for this.

00:30:17.100 --> 00:30:21.000
So Kubernetes went
out into the world

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:24.690
with a half dozen
corporate entities

00:30:24.690 --> 00:30:26.830
really working
closely with Google.

00:30:26.830 --> 00:30:32.040
So our 1.0 launch had all of
these corporate collaborators.

00:30:32.040 --> 00:30:36.120
And that worked great because we
all understood how this worked.

00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:40.320
We were all signing the Google
contributor license agreement.

00:30:40.320 --> 00:30:42.180
It was all OK.

00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:47.370
But the idea that Kubernetes
was to be industry changing

00:30:47.370 --> 00:30:51.480
and actually move the way
we thought about portable

00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:56.160
workloads in the cloud meant
that we needed more, and more,

00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:59.970
and more companies-- especially
very large companies,

00:30:59.970 --> 00:31:04.320
especially companies who may
or may not compete with Google

00:31:04.320 --> 00:31:11.520
in different consumer areas
and business product areas--

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:15.060
means that it got to be
a lot more contentious.

00:31:15.060 --> 00:31:17.310
So, I want to contribute
to your thing.

00:31:17.310 --> 00:31:19.410
I want to help you
achieve your goals

00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:22.330
but I can't sign your license.

00:31:22.330 --> 00:31:27.720
And so we got stuck with a few
corporate contributors saying,

00:31:27.720 --> 00:31:30.380
that's great but we can't.

00:31:30.380 --> 00:31:34.020
And Kubernetes, because we
knew we wanted this-- again,

00:31:34.020 --> 00:31:36.610
going back to, what
was the strategic goal?

00:31:36.610 --> 00:31:38.610
Going back to what the
strategic goal was,

00:31:38.610 --> 00:31:41.260
we wanted this to
change the industry.

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:43.920
And so we knew that to
do that we had to let

00:31:43.920 --> 00:31:45.450
go of some of the control.

00:31:45.450 --> 00:31:49.320
And that was the creation of the
Cloud Native Compute Foundation

00:31:49.320 --> 00:31:51.330
at the Linux Foundation.

00:31:51.330 --> 00:31:56.520
And that then allowed us to
take the same language we

00:31:56.520 --> 00:31:59.710
use for the Google
Contributor License Agreement,

00:31:59.710 --> 00:32:02.220
cross-out Google, say
Cloud Native Compute

00:32:02.220 --> 00:32:06.540
Foundation in all the locations,
change the tooling so that it

00:32:06.540 --> 00:32:10.290
was the Cloud Native
Compute Foundation License,

00:32:10.290 --> 00:32:14.460
transfer all the licenses with
all the existing contributors.

00:32:14.460 --> 00:32:17.100
And now those
companies that were not

00:32:17.100 --> 00:32:21.060
happy about signing a Google
Contributor License Agreement

00:32:21.060 --> 00:32:25.200
were perfectly content
to sign the same language

00:32:25.200 --> 00:32:29.100
as long as that transfer of
IP went to the Cloud Native

00:32:29.100 --> 00:32:31.020
Compute Foundation.

00:32:31.020 --> 00:32:34.650
And that was a fine
solution for this.

00:32:34.650 --> 00:32:39.930
A lot of younger projects,
more recent projects,

00:32:39.930 --> 00:32:44.550
have focused on
DCOs and not CLAs--

00:32:44.550 --> 00:32:46.800
Developer Certificates
of Origin,

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:49.680
instead of Contributor License
Agreements, or Corporate

00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:51.750
Contributor License Agreements.

00:32:51.750 --> 00:32:54.870
And that's not
something that Google

00:32:54.870 --> 00:32:58.110
is comfortable with because
there's not a lot of case

00:32:58.110 --> 00:32:59.920
law about it at this point.

00:32:59.920 --> 00:33:03.700
And a lot of the case law is
being litigated right now.

00:33:03.700 --> 00:33:06.160
And until there is a clear path.

00:33:06.160 --> 00:33:08.160
Until there is a
clear way that you

00:33:08.160 --> 00:33:11.670
can handle the, oops, we need
to relicense this, or oops,

00:33:11.670 --> 00:33:14.580
we need to make a big
change without having

00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:18.900
to contact the thousands
of contributors that

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:20.820
may have contributed
to a project,

00:33:20.820 --> 00:33:25.968
until that case law exists,
it's too big of risk.

00:33:25.968 --> 00:33:28.450
CHRIS DIBONA: Have you seen
any problems with this?

00:33:28.450 --> 00:33:31.300
CASSANDRA SALISBURY: Well,
Go sits a little differently

00:33:31.300 --> 00:33:33.720
in the bucket than I think
everything else's projects do.

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:34.440
SARAH NOVOTNY: See, no one way.

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:35.523
CASSANDRA SALISBURY: Yeah.

00:33:35.523 --> 00:33:37.210
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:40.110
We, being that we're a
programming language,

00:33:40.110 --> 00:33:41.850
it is a little bit different.

00:33:41.850 --> 00:33:46.000
But I can say that last
summer, before I joined Google,

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:47.520
I sat in a room--

00:33:47.520 --> 00:33:49.110
Will, you alluded to this--

00:33:49.110 --> 00:33:55.860
